text.text: A Guide to Camden

Camden's not what it used to be, but let's be honest, neither are you and neither are we. Perhaps it's the swarms of tourists, or the influx of money; perhaps it's the smell of wacky greenery, or the inebriated fuckery. But under the overpriced eateries and the Deathly Hallows tees, Camden's a bit of a beaut' and a charming old ditty. So let's have it large now, shall we?
Best for... cheesy halloumi goodness

tip.text:
When he's not busy foraging for blueberries in Hackney, Oliver Stevens, aka Oli Baba is busy running tings in Kerb's Camden Market. His meat-free Levantine cuisine attracts tourists and locals alike, which explains the mahoosive queue usually waiting in front of his shack - the one with the Peas Be Upon You sign, 'cuz he's hilarious like that. After deciding to drop out of uni to eat his way through the Middle East, Oli has spent years perfecting his craft and has become a master of the halloumi fry.

These fat, juicy slithers of cheese are crispy on the outside and warm and comforting on the inside, paired with the zing of pomegranate, the freshness of mint and soft, creamy za'atar yoghurt. These bad boys are bound to make your little heart sang. If halloumi's not your bag - we can't be your friend - but you could order yourself some fattoush with a side of Oli Baba's signature schug (a delicious Middle Eastern salsa verde). Or you could just choose something else in the market - it's not like there are no other options.

text.text: When he's not off foraging in Hackney, Oli Baba is busy running tings in his halloumi fry shack at Camden Market. These fat, juicy slithers of cheese are crispy on the outside and comforting on the inside, paired with the zing of pomegranate, the freshness of mint and soft, creamy za'atar yoghurt. If that doesn't float your boat, you can always get something else from the market - it's not like there are no other options.
Best for... a spot of culture

tip.text:
Times change, but do they really? That's one of the questions we were forced to ponder as we stared down into the medieval mikveh of Camden Town's Jewish Museum. There were other questions that popped up, like how does one define a community without defining a home, why on Earth is Shakespeare in Yiddish not a thing anymore, and how do we still feel the need to act like schmucks with marginalised people?

We may not have found all our answers, but we did find a bunch of really interesting stuff. This two-floor museum boasts one of the finest Jewish collections in the world; including a beautiful portrait of a Jewish Algerian woman in 1843, the intimate story of East End Auschwitz survivor Leon Greenman told through his personal artefacts, and a 17th-century Venetian synagogue ark which was once mistakenly used as a cupboard. With over two thousand pieces and a new exhibition every six months, the Museum offers an intricate snapshot of the Jewish community, from its faith, to its history and its innate complexity.

text.text:
Times change, but do they really? That's one of the questions you might wish to contemplate as you stare down into the medieval mikveh of London's one and only Jewish Museum. 

Other questions might pop up as you stroll through this two-floor institution boasting one of the finest collections of Jewish art and artefacts in the world. Like why do we still act like schmucks to marginalised people and how is Shakespeare in Yiddish not a thing anymore? Plenty of existential stuff to consider, but we have bigger fish to fry.
Best for... fried fishy tings

tip.text:
Fish and chips, save the gallon of grease that comes with your usual corner-chippie purchase. With Colombian spices, Mexican sauces, and the occasional Japanese tempura, we were a little stunned for choice upon entry but well satisfied upon exit. This was partly due to the side of cod cheeks - they’re the tits. There's plenty of 'healthy deli' options - salads and the like - to be had if you're after something lighter.

Hook's sure got them Brighton-beach-house vibes, only with way better fish and instead of an ocean soundscape you’ve got 90’s bangers for your aural pleasure. Well worth the jaunt to Camden.

text.text:
Hook's chef Gordon is so into fish and chips you'd think he was pulling your fin. This former drum & bass DJ is quite the character and, more importantly, a pretty exceptional cook. 

Dive headfirst into some freshly fried skate in panko (a flakey Japenese bread crumb) with seaweed salted chips dipped in spicy pineapple and ginger ketchup, which is sweet, sour, salty and succulent. Pair that with a homemade raspberry and thyme lemonade, add a shot of gin, add another, and walk away before you order more popcorn cockles.
Best for... impressing a vegan date

tip.text:
Around the corner from the tourist-laden Camden Lock, Mildreds is a refreshingly chilled out spot. Bright and airy, the décor oozes cool with modern fittings and quirky wall art. Vegetarian and vegan dishes make up the menu but there've been no corners cut in their commitment to big, punchy flavours. The beetroot burger, roasted mushroom and ale pie, sweet potato curry and summer salad are all winners, but it’s the raw chocolate truffle cake that takes the crown.

Reservations are taken, but with snappy service and part of the restaurant reserved for walk ins, you should be fine to turn up on the night.

text.text:
Too much fish can spoil the broth, that's why veg is better. This hub of coppery decadence dishes out chill vibes and veggie deliciousness in a sophisticated setting, complete with quirky wall fittings and surprisingly comfy seating. 

The beetroot burger, mushroom and ale pie, sweet potato curry and summer salad are all winners, but it’s the vegan raw chocolate truffle cake that takes the crown. Whoever said you can't have your cake and eat it should really shut up and pop into Mildreds.
Best for... a G&T, or two, or three

tip.text:
Take a stroll round any backstreet in Camden for 10 minutes and chances are you’ll run into a decent gastropub – this is one of the better ones. Decked out in shades of turquoise and with a healthy crop of leather couches you can sink into, this is a comfortable place for your Sunday lunch or evening G&T.

There’s a strong emphasis on gin (over 30 varieties at last count - must do better, really), and the menu is high-quality pub fare that aims to please everyone. The more refined sort might plump for the confit of salmon but you’ll find us face down in the deep-fried mac and cheese balls with Sriracha-mayo, thankyouverymuch. Chuck in a great outdoor area, a gorgeous Sunday roast, some pub quizzes and many a gin tasting and, yeah, this place is all-right.

text.text:
If you're a bit of a Dojo aficionado - which you are, we have data, we know things - then you know we have a bit of a soft spot for a hidden gem, a saucy Sunday roast and many a glorious gin. 

So we're off to find the ol' Colonel Fawcett, a splendid gastropub just off Camden Rd decked out in shades of turquoise and snug burgundy sofas. Pick one of the 30 gins they have on offer, then nip out into the lavish garden to enjoy a few seconds of silence under the fairy lights and the bougie, burgeoning pergola.
Best for... satisfying that sweet tooth

tip.text:
It really wasn't that long ago that we were all flipping flabbergasted by Heston Blumenthal's nitro-ice cream, but now it's a thing, a thing Chin Chin Labs are well and truly excelling in. This itsy bitsy ice cream shop might be sat at the epicentre of Tourist Central, but don't let that put you off; not when there's so much creamy deliciousness to shove down your gob.

Chin Chin like to channel all their good chi into a few special weekly recipes: one chocolate, one vanilla and two miscellaneous treats - one of which is usually dairy-free to please Camden's notorious vegan colony. The liquid nitrogen is used to freeze the ice cream as it's being churned, meaning no crunchy ice crystals, just the creamiest of concoctions that melts in your mouth, because you've eaten it long before it can melt in your hand.

Do be warned, it's cash only and prices aren't cheap (£5 per scoop), because you're in Camden, silly.

text.text: After summin sweet, summin sexy and summin a little scientific? Then you're a bit of a strange one, but we're into it. As is Chin Chin, an isty bitsy retro shop bang in the middle of the market that specialises in nitro ice cream, a magically soft and creamy concoction that melts in your mouth coz you've finished it long before it can melt in your hand. It is a bit spenny and they only do four weekly options, but don't let that put you off, not when there's so much smooth, scrumptious stuff to shove down your gob.
Best for... a taste of Brazzziu

tip.text:
Made in Brasil was actually made down the street, in Camden - this is its little sister venue, Made in Brasil Boteco. The focus here is on small Brazilian tapas and a long, long list of caipirinhas - they even claim to have the biggest collection of cachaca in the UK, which is quite the claim. The kind of claim no one can be asked to check, not even humble, diligent, talented apps like ourselves.

Still, we thought we'd give some of this cachaca a taste, but with 350 bottles to choose from, we panicked, and asked the waitress to pick for us. She came back with a chilli raspberry caipirinha, made from chilli infused Pitù cachaça, raspberry purée, fresh lime and white sugar, which was gone in no time; along with a small plate of isca de peixe camarao and deliciously tender camarao alho e olea. Don't know what that is? You'll just have to come, take a seat in the glass tower, order a drink, and ask.

text.text:
There's an old saying in Brazil: who drinks cachaças, must also have tapas - or something similar, we can't really remember. This shabby shack opposite the market specialises in fishy tapasy tings and has over 350 types of cachaças on offer, which is a lot. One might even say it's too much. 

Perch in their slightly seedy rooftop conservatory and grab yourself a sleek and tangy chilli-infused raspberry caipirinha. You know, for the road - the long, strenuous road to the next cocktail bar round the corner.
Best for... fast food, vegan-style

tip.text:
Chicken shops are a dime a dozen in London, but there's one newcomer that's cornered a fresh angle. With their vegan fried chicken and classic chip shop sides, Temple of Seitan completely blew up social media as they opened the doors to their first outpost in Hackney. Now the folk of Camden can have a piece of the pie and actually sit in to enjoy it.

It's a much bigger space, with muralled walls and the usual friendly, tattooed staff. Yep, the omnipresent gaggles of young tourists in Camden are going to lap it up. The seitan "chicken" lives up to the real thing, albeit much more bird friendly (and a little pricier) than your OG chicken and chips. Go for burgers of the stuff, strips, popcorn bites or decadent mac 'n' cheese - just don't expect it to be healthy.

Best for... tequila & chillin' with the chulas

tip.text:
Camden can be a bit of a maze. You're probably more in need of our expertise here than in many other London locations. Lucky for you we've scoped out Cafe Chula and found it holding promise. What's so promising about it? Tacos.

They may not be the cheapest tacs in town but filling and tasteful is something we look for too. Braised pulled pork and pineapple, green peppers and chihuahua cheese and the winner - beer-battered fish with red cabbage, lime-chipotle mayo, guacamole and pico de gallo. There's many a tequila cocktail to choose from too - we were happy with our El Acido - a tequila raspberry sour which we happily demolished, but if you want a night out out, go for their classic Margherita, because it's just bloody lush.

text.text:
With colourful tiles adorning the walls, a fiercely friendly vibe, casual coffee, tasty tacos and three pages of tantalising tequilas, mezcals and other agave-based spirits to choose from, this Mexican joint has all sorts going for it. And the guys who work here are real experts, so put yourself in their hands.

After much careful, deliberate consideration, we'd recommend going for their signature margarita or their take on a tequila raspberry sour. If all else fails, the last, slightly illegible words in our notebook are 'Reposado is nice', so maybe just try that?
Best for... dope steak

tip.text:
Admitting to liking steak these days is akin to admitting to liking golf; we'd advise only telling your nearest and dearest, and even then expecting to lose a couple of close friends. But *whispering* we are partial to the occasional slab, and this is a brilliant place for it - a rustic, homestyle Argentine restaurant where the expat Argentines dine, with a menu full of tasty grilled cuts of the highest order.

This is steak every which way (along with chicken and pork), receiving the heat-ment from a parrilla charcoal grill. If you really want to go in, share the Parrillada Pampa which comes as a mixed grill of beef ribs, rump, chorizo, black pudding and bondiola pork. All wine, meanwhile, is sourced from Mendoza, in the western Argentinean foothills of the Andes. The setting is suitably cosy and atmospheric too with bare brick, worn woods and a lively hubbub erupting as locals gorge on good steak and good red wine.
